04430nam a22006255i 9780271031163DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212001pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710311637 a10.1515/97802710311632doi  a(DE-B1597)583904  a(OCoLC)1262308463  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPHI0150002bisacsh04a171/.62221 aLangston, Douglas C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aConscience and Other Virtues :bFrom Bonaventure to MacIntyre /cDouglas C. Langston. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2001  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPART I: HISTORICAL BACKGROUND -- t1 Classical Background to Discussions of Conscience -- t2 Bonaventure's View of Conscience and Synderesis -- t3 Aquinas on Conscience, the Virtues, and Weakness of Will -- t4 Scotus and Ockham on Synderesis and Conscience -- t5 Luther and the Rise of Conscience as a Faculty -- tPART II: THE CONTEMPORARY DISMISSAL OF CONSCIENCE -- t6 Freud and Ryle on Conscience -- t7 Conscience as Something Other Than a Faculty -- t8 More Traditional Views of Conscience -- t9 The Existence of Conscience -- tPART III: CONSCIENCE AS A KEY TO VIRTUE ETHICS -- t10 Conscience Among the Virtue Ethicists -- t11 Conscience and Virtue Ethics -- t12 Conscience and Other Virtues -- tAppendix: Macintyre's Project -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aConscience, once a core concept for ethics, has mostly disappeared from modern moral theory. In this book Douglas Langston traces its intellectual history to account for its neglect while arguing for its still vital importance, if correctly understood.In medieval times, Langston shows in Part I, the notions of ";conscientia"; and ";synderesis"; from which our contemporary concept of conscience derives were closely connected to Greek ideas about the virtues and practical reason, although in Christianized form. As modified by Luther, Butler, and Kant, however, conscience later came to be regarded as a faculty like will and intellect, and when faculty psychology fell into disrepute, so did the role of conscience in moral philosophy.A view of mature conscience that sees it as relational, with cognitive, emotional, and conative dimensions, can survive the criticisms of conscience as faculty. In Part II, through discussions of Freud, Ryle, and other modern thinkers, Langston proceeds to reconstruct conscience as a viable philosophical concept.Finally, in Part III, this better grounded concept is connected with the modern revival of virtue ethics, and Langston shows how crucial conscience is to a theory of virtue because it is fundamental to the training of any morally good person.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Mind & Body.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271031163zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271031163423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271031163.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK